'''Modesta Bor''' ([[Juan Griego]], [[Isla de Margarita]], 1926 – [[Mérida, Mérida|Mérida]], 1998) was a [[Venezuela]]n compositor.
==Life and career== Modesta Bor was born in Juan Griego, Isla de Margarita. She studied in [[Caracas]] with [[Elena Arrarte]], [[Juan Bautista Plaza]], [[Antonio Estévez]], [[Maria de Lourdes Rotundo]] and [[Vicente Emilio Sojo]], graduating with a degree in composition in 1959. She continued her studies at the [[Moscow Conservatory|Moscow Tchaikovsky Conservatory]] with [[Aram Khachaturian]].<ref>{{cite book |title=A Guide to Piano Music by Women Composers: Women born after 1900|author=Dees, Pamela Youngdahl|year=2004}}</ref> In 1960 she won her first National Music Prize with ''Sonata for violin and piano''.
After completing her studies, Bor returned to Venezuela to work as a composer, teacher and choir director, becoming head of the music department in the [[Central University of Venezuela]] Culture Department. She also served as director of the musicology section of Folklore Research of the National Service. She died in [[Mérida, Mérida|Mérida]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mundoarts.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=33%3Amodestabor&catid=14%3Acomposers&Itemid=46&lang=en|title=Modesta Bor (Venezuela, 1926-1998)|accessdate=29 January 2011}}</ref>
==Works== Bor composed for orchestra, chamber ensemble, piano and vocal performance, writing more than 95 choral works for mixed and 130 for equal-voice choir.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://drc.ohiolink.edu/handle/2374.OX/10996|title=A Conductor's Guide to Selected Choral Works of Modesta Bor|accessdate=29 January 2011}}</ref> Selected works include: *''Children's Suite'' *''Canción de cuna para dormir un negrito'' (in ''Tríptico sobre poesía cubana'', for voice and piano) (Text: Nicolas Guillén) *''Coplas venezolanas'' (in ''Segundo cico de romanzas y canciones'', for contralto and piano) (Text: Andrés Eloy Blanco Meaño) *''Guitarra'' (in ''Tríptico sobre poesía cubana'' for voice and piano) (Text: Nicolas Guillén) *''Nocturno en los muellas'' (in ''Tríptico sobre poesía cubana'' for voice and piano) (Text: Nicolas Guillén) *''Pregón'' (in ''Segundo ciclo de romanzas y canciones'' for contralto and piano) (Text: Andrés Eloy Blanco Meaño) *''Si el silencio fuera mío'' (in ''Segundo ciclo de romanzas y canciones'' for contralgo and piano) (Text: Andrés Eloy Blanco Meaño) *''Suspiro cuando te miro'' (in ''Segundo ciclo de romanzas y canciones'' for contralto and piano) (Text: Andrés Eloy Blanco Meaño)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lieder.net/lieder/b/bor.html|title=Composer: Modesta Bor (1926-1998)|accessdate=29 January 2011}}</ref>
